name: 4.Model Training and Evaluation
content:
Model Training:


In this analysis, we employed the H2O Distributed Random Forest classifier and H20 XG Boost model. The subsequent sections provide a comprehensive overview of the model's performance on both training and testing datasets.


H2O XGBoost

  • Overview:
  • H2O XGBoost is a highly optimized, scalable implementation of the Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) algorithm. It combines the strengths of gradient boosting with H2O’s distributed computing framework, making it suitable for large-scale healthcare datasets.
  • Key Strengths:
  • Efficient handling of non-linear relationships between patient and hospital features.
  • Incorporates regularization to prevent overfitting.
  • Supports parallelized tree building, ensuring faster training.
  • Effective for datasets with categorical + numerical mix.

H2O Distributed Random Forest (DRF) Classifier

  • Overview:
  • H2O DRF is an implementation of the Random Forest algorithm optimized for distributed environments. It trains multiple decision trees on bootstrapped subsets of data and aggregates their predictions for robust classification.
  • Key Strengths:
  • Handles large datasets efficiently using distributed processing.
  • Naturally robust against overfitting due to ensemble averaging.
  • Provides feature importance scores, aiding interpretability of healthcare stay predictors.
  • Supports categorical variables directly, reducing preprocessing effort.

H2O Scoring

  • Process:
  • Once trained, both models were evaluated using H2O scoring functions on test data. The evaluation metrics included:
  • Accuracy → Correct predictions of stay duration.
  • Confusion Matrix → Distribution of correct/incorrect predictions by category (e.g., Short, Medium, Long stay).
  • AUC-ROC → Performance measure for distinguishing between stay categories (where applicable).
  • LogLoss → Used to assess the model’s predictive confidence.

H2O Model Saving

  • After validation, the models were saved using h2o.saveModel().
  • Benefits of saving models:
  • Reusability → No need for retraining when deploying in production.
  • Portability → Models can be easily transferred across environments.
  • Operational Efficiency → Faster integration into hospital IT systems for real-time predictions.

Model Prediction :


Model prediction using H2O Score and H2O Model Load involves the process of first loading a previously saved model using the H2O Model Load function and then applying this model to new data to generate predictions. The predictions are evaluated using H2O Score, which provides performance metrics and insights into how well the model performs on the new data.


H2O Score : It refers to the process of evaluating a trained machine learning model by generating predictions on a dataset and calculating various performance metrics, such as accuracy, AUC-ROC, or mean squared error, depending on the task. This evaluation helps assess the model’s effectiveness and predictive accuracy.


H2O Model Load : It is the process of retrieving a previously saved machine learning model from storage so that it can be used for making predictions on new data. This function allows the model to be reloaded without the need to retrain, facilitating reuse in production environments.
